To add transparency to the background color of an element, you can use the `rgba()` function in CSS.

The `rgba()` function stands for "Red Green Blue Alpha", where the `Alpha` value specifies the transparency level of the color. The Alpha value is a number between 0 and 1, where 0 is completely transparent, and 1 is completely opaque.

Here's an example of how to add transparency to the background color of an element:
```css
.element {
  background-color: rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.5);
}
```
In this example, we're setting the `background-color` property of the `.element` class to a light gray color with an alpha value of 0.5, which is 50% transparent.

You can adjust the Red, Green, and Blue values to choose any color you want, and adjust the Alpha value to make the color more or less transparent. The higher the Alpha value, the less transparent the color will be.

Note that not all browsers support the `rgba()` function, so you may want to provide a fallback color using the `background-color` property, like this:
```css
.element {
  background-color: rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.5);
  /* Fallback color for browsers that don't support rgba() */
  background-color: #ffffff; /* This will be used if rgba() is not supported */
  opacity: 0.5; /* Fallback for older versions of IE */
}
```
In this example, we're providing a fallback color of white using the `background-color` property, and using the `opacity` property as a fallback for older versions of Internet Explorer that don't support the `rgba()` function.

To make the navbar transparent only when not scrolling, you can remove the `background-color` property from the `.sticky-navbar` and add it to a new class that you will add and remove using JavaScript based on the scroll position. Here's how you can modify the code:

1. Add a new CSS class called `.transparent-navbar` with a transparent background color:
```css
.transparent-navbar {
  background-color: transparent !important;
}
```
In this example, we're setting the `background-color` property of the `.transparent-navbar` class to `transparent` using the `!important` keyword to override any other background color properties.

1. Modify the JavaScript code to add and remove the `.transparent-navbar` class based on the scroll position:
```javascript
$(document).ready(function () {
  // Handle the navbar shrink effect on scroll
  $(window).scroll(function () {
    if ($(this).scrollTop() > 50) {
      $('.sticky-navbar').addClass('shrink');
      $('.sticky-navbar').removeClass('navbar-shadows');
      $('.sticky-navbar').removeClass('transparent-navbar');
    } else {
      $('.sticky-navbar').removeClass('shrink');
      $('.sticky-navbar').addClass('navbar-shadows');
      $('.sticky-navbar').addClass('transparent-navbar');
    }
  });
});
```
In this example, we're using the `scrollTop()` method to get the current scroll position of the window. When the user scrolls down the page, we remove the `.transparent-navbar` class from the navbar element to make the background color opaque, and when the user scrolls back to the top of the page, we add the `.transparent-navbar` class to make the background color transparent.

And that's it! Your navbar should now have a transparent background color only when not scrolling. Note that you can adjust the class names and CSS styles to suit your needs.

