You can add a video background to a `div` using HTML5's `<video>` element and CSS. Here's an example:
```html
<div class="video-background">
  <video autoplay muted loop>
    <source src="video.mp4" type="video/mp4">
    Your browser does not support the video tag.
  </video>
</div>
```
In this example, we're creating a `div` with a class of `video-background`. Inside the `div`, we're adding a `<video>` element with three attributes: `autoplay`, `muted`, and `loop`. These attributes will cause the video to start playing automatically, mute the audio, and loop the video when it reaches the end.

We're also adding a `<source>` element inside the `<video>` element with the path to the video file and its MIME type. Finally, we're adding a fallback message for browsers that do not support the `<video>` element.

To make the `div` fill the entire screen, you can add the following CSS:
```css
.video-background {
  position: fixed;
  top: 0;
  left: 0;
  width: 100%;
  height: 100%;
  z-index: -1;
}

.video-background video {
  object-fit: cover;
}
```
This will position the `div` at the top-left corner of the screen, with a width and height of 100% to cover the entire screen. The `z-index` property is set to -1 to make sure the video stays in the background.

The `object-fit: cover` property in the `video` selector is used to make the video fill the entire `div` without distorting its aspect ratio.

Note that different video formats may be required for different browsers. It's a good practice to provide multiple `<source>` elements with different video formats to ensure the video will play on different browsers.
